{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17474970","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17474970"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:27:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:27:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12476"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12476","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12476"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.23,0.04,0.55,0.03,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4983"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"38958"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4983","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4983"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12476"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"23287"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1842"},{"type":"tags","id":"5810"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8243"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8984"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14558"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"38958","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/38958"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 3-year-old child is brought to the Emergency Department by her parents, who are concerned that she has been crying persistently and is inconsolable. She started crying when she was playing outside with her brother earlier that day and he dragged her by her arm when she refused to get inside. She told mother that her left arm hurt and she has not allowed anyone to touch that arm since then. On examination, she is holding her left arm close to her body with the elbow slightly flexed and the forearm pronated. There is no focal bony tenderness, ecchymosis, erythema, deformity, or swelling over the distal humerus and proximal ulna.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Posterior splint and sling immobilisation","Closed reduction with percutaneous pinning","Closed reduction by supination/flexion","Open reduction and internal fixation","Cast immobilisation with the elbow in flexion"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EA history of the child\u0027s arm being pulled upwards by the wrist or the child being swung around by the arms just prior to the onset of the symptoms, combined with examination findings such as the arm held close to the body with the elbow either fully extended or slightly flexed and the forearm pronated, points to a \u003Cstrong\u003Eradial head subluxation \u003C/strong\u003E(pulled elbow/nursemaid\u0027s elbow) diagnosis. The absence of any focal bony tenderness, ecchymosis, erythema, deformity, or swelling over the distal humerus and proximal ulna rules out the differential diagnosis of fracture and soft tissue injury. An X-ray is not needed in the case of a pulled elbow and would only be done if there was thought to be a fracture.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClosed reduction by \u003C/strong\u003Ehyperpronation and supination/flexion are two common techniques preferred for reduction of a subluxed radial head.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETo use the supination/flexion method, apply gentle pressure to the radial head with the physician\u0027s thumb while supporting the elbow with the same hand. The patient\u0027s distal forearm should be grasped with the other hand. After that, the patient\u0027s forearm should be supinated and fully flexed while gentle traction is applied. If the maneuver is successful, a click may be felt or heard.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETo use the hyperpronation method, apply moderate pressure to the radial head while supporting the child\u0027s elbow with the same hand. By applying force to the wrist with the opposite hand, the forearm should be hyperpronated. A click felt over the radial head usually indicates that the maneuver was successful.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDifferential diagnoses include fractures (lateral condylar, medial condylar, wrist, supracondylar, monteggia) and soft tissue injuries of the hand. Non-displaced supracondylar fractures are managed with \u003Cstrong\u003Eposterior splinting and sling immobilization.\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECast immobilization with the elbow in flexion\u003C/strong\u003E and the forearm in neutral position with respect to supination and pronation is done for non-displaced, impacted, and greenstick types of medial condylar fracture. Open reduction and internal fixation may be needed if there is displacement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClosed reduction with percutaneous pinning\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003Eopen reduction and internal fixation\u003C/strong\u003E are used for significantly displaced lateral condylar and supracondylar fractures.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Closed reduction by hyperpronation and supination/flexion are two common techniques preferred for reduction of a subluxed radial head.","The diagnosis of a pulled elbow is mostly clinical; radiographic evaluation is only advised if there is suspicion of a fracture."],"references":["Green NE. Fractures and dislocations about the elbow. In: Skeletal Trauma in Children, 3rd ed, Green NE, Swiontkowski MF (Eds), WB Saunders, Philadelphia 2003. p.257.","Macias CG, Wiebe R, Bothner J. History and radiographic findings associated with clinically suspected radial head subluxations. Pediatr Emerg Care 2000; 16:22.","Mintzer CM, Waters PM, Brown DJ, Kasser JR. Percutaneous pinning in the treatment of displaced lateral condyle fractures. J Pediatr Orthop 1994; 14:462.","Goodwin RC, Kuivila TE. Pediatric elbow and forearm fractures requiring surgical treatment. Hand Clin 2002; 18:135.","Naomi M. Nardi; Timothy J. Schaefer: Nursemaid Elbow [Internet]. StatPearls Publishing LLC. 2022 [updated August 22, 2022; cited March 8, 2023]. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK430777/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"23287"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12476"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"23287","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/23287"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-08-18T11:41:02+09:30","updatedAt":"2023-08-18T11:41:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4983"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"38958"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updat